<BaseLayout title="Unit Conversion Cheat Sheet: The Most Common Conversions You Need" description="A quick-reference guide to the most common unit conversions for length, weight, volume, temperature, and cooking measurements, with exact factors and practical tips." structuredData={structuredData}>
  <article class="blog-article">
    <header class="article-header">
      <p class="article-meta">Published February 20, 2026 · Updated March 1, 2026 · By ToolCalcs Team</p>
      <h1>Unit Conversion Cheat Sheet: The Most Common Conversions You Need</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Whether you are following a recipe from another country, shopping for furniture online, or interpreting a weather forecast in Celsius, unit conversions come up constantly. This cheat sheet gathers the most common conversions in one place with exact factors and easy-to-remember approximations.</p>
    </header>

    <h2>Length Conversions</h2>
    <p>The United States uses inches, feet, yards, and miles while most of the world uses the metric system. Here are the exact conversion factors you need.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>From</th>
          <th>To</th>
          <th>Multiply By</th>
          <th>Example</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Inches</td><td>Centimeters</td><td>2.54</td><td>12 in = 30.48 cm</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Centimeters</td><td>Inches</td><td>0.3937</td><td>30 cm = 11.81 in</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Feet</td><td>Meters</td><td>0.3048</td><td>6 ft = 1.8288 m</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Meters</td><td>Feet</td><td>3.2808</td><td>2 m = 6.56 ft</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Yards</td><td>Meters</td><td>0.9144</td><td>100 yd = 91.44 m</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Miles</td><td>Kilometers</td><td>1.6093</td><td>5 mi = 8.05 km</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Kilometers</td><td>Miles</td><td>0.6214</td><td>10 km = 6.21 mi</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Quick Tips for Length</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>1 inch is about 2.5 cm. For a rough estimate, multiply inches by 2.5.</li>
      <li>1 meter is roughly 3 feet 3 inches — just a bit longer than a yard.</li>
      <li>A kilometer is about 0.6 miles. To convert km to miles quickly, multiply by 6 and drop the last digit (10 km &times; 6 = 60 &rarr; 6.0 miles).</li>
      <li>5 miles is almost exactly 8 km. The Fibonacci trick: consecutive Fibonacci numbers approximate mile-to-km conversions (5 mi &asymp; 8 km, 8 mi &asymp; 13 km).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Weight Conversions</h2>
    <p>Weight is one of the most frequent conversion needs, especially for cooking, shipping, and fitness tracking.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>From</th>
          <th>To</th>
          <th>Multiply By</th>
          <th>Example</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Pounds</td><td>Kilograms</td><td>0.4536</td><td>150 lb = 68.04 kg</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Kilograms</td><td>Pounds</td><td>2.2046</td><td>70 kg = 154.32 lb</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Ounces</td><td>Grams</td><td>28.3495</td><td>8 oz = 226.80 g</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Grams</td><td>Ounces</td><td>0.0353</td><td>500 g = 17.64 oz</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Pounds</td><td>Ounces</td><td>16</td><td>3 lb = 48 oz</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Quick Tips for Weight</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>1 kg is about 2.2 pounds. To quickly estimate, double the kilograms and add 10%. (70 kg &rarr; 140 + 14 = 154 lb.)</li>
      <li>1 ounce is about 28 grams. A standard letter weighs roughly 1 oz / 28 g.</li>
      <li>A pound is about 454 grams — just under half a kilogram.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Volume Conversions</h2>
    <p>Volume conversions are essential in the kitchen and come up frequently when comparing product sizes across countries.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>From</th>
          <th>To</th>
          <th>Multiply By</th>
          <th>Example</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Cups (US)</td><td>Milliliters</td><td>236.588</td><td>2 cups = 473 mL</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tablespoons</td><td>Milliliters</td><td>14.787</td><td>3 tbsp = 44.36 mL</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Teaspoons</td><td>Milliliters</td><td>4.929</td><td>2 tsp = 9.86 mL</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Fluid ounces</td><td>Milliliters</td><td>29.574</td><td>8 fl oz = 236.59 mL</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Gallons (US)</td><td>Liters</td><td>3.7854</td><td>1 gal = 3.79 L</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Liters</td><td>Gallons (US)</td><td>0.2642</td><td>2 L = 0.53 gal</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Quarts</td><td>Liters</td><td>0.9464</td><td>1 qt = 0.95 L</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Quick Tips for Volume</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>1 liter is just a hair more than 1 quart — they are nearly interchangeable for rough estimates.</li>
      <li>1 US cup is about 237 mL, which is close to 240 mL (a common metric "cup" size in some countries).</li>
      <li>A gallon is roughly 3.8 liters. A 2-liter soda bottle is about half a gallon.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Cooking Measurement Conversions</h2>
    <p>These conversions within the US customary system come up every time you scale a recipe up or down.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Measurement</th>
          <th>Equivalent</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1 tablespoon</td><td>3 teaspoons</td></tr>
        <tr><td>1 cup</td><td>16 tablespoons</td></tr>
        <tr><td>1 cup</td><td>8 fluid ounces</td></tr>
        <tr><td>1 pint</td><td>2 cups</td></tr>
        <tr><td>1 quart</td><td>4 cups / 2 pints</td></tr>
        <tr><td>1 gallon</td><td>4 quarts / 16 cups</td></tr>
        <tr><td>1 stick of butter</td><td>8 tablespoons / &frac12; cup / 4 oz</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>When halving a recipe, the trickiest conversion is half of &frac34; cup. The answer is 6 tablespoons (since &frac34; cup = 12 tablespoons).</p>

    <h2>Temperature Conversions</h2>
    <p>Temperature is the one conversion where you cannot just multiply by a single number — you also have to add or subtract an offset.</p>

    <h3>Formulas</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Fahrenheit to Celsius:</strong> &deg;C = (&deg;F &minus; 32) &times; 5/9</li>
      <li><strong>Celsius to Fahrenheit:</strong> &deg;F = (&deg;C &times; 9/5) + 32</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Common Temperature Benchmarks</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Fahrenheit</th>
          <th>Celsius</th>
          <th>What It Means</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>32&deg;F</td><td>0&deg;C</td><td>Water freezes</td></tr>
        <tr><td>50&deg;F</td><td>10&deg;C</td><td>Cool day, light jacket</td></tr>
        <tr><td>68&deg;F</td><td>20&deg;C</td><td>Room temperature</td></tr>
        <tr><td>72&deg;F</td><td>22&deg;C</td><td>Comfortable indoors</td></tr>
        <tr><td>86&deg;F</td><td>30&deg;C</td><td>Hot summer day</td></tr>
        <tr><td>98.6&deg;F</td><td>37&deg;C</td><td>Normal body temperature</td></tr>
        <tr><td>212&deg;F</td><td>100&deg;C</td><td>Water boils</td></tr>
        <tr><td>350&deg;F</td><td>177&deg;C</td><td>Common oven baking temp</td></tr>
        <tr><td>400&deg;F</td><td>204&deg;C</td><td>Higher oven baking temp</td></tr>
        <tr><td>450&deg;F</td><td>232&deg;C</td><td>Pizza / high-heat roasting</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Quick Mental Math for Temperature</h3>
    <p>For a rough Fahrenheit-to-Celsius estimate: subtract 30, then divide by 2. Example: 72&deg;F &rarr; (72 &minus; 30) / 2 = 21&deg;C. (The exact answer is 22.2&deg;C — close enough for deciding what to wear.)</p>
    <p>For Celsius-to-Fahrenheit: double it and add 30. Example: 25&deg;C &rarr; (25 &times; 2) + 30 = 80&deg;F. (Exact: 77&deg;F.)</p>

    <h2>Quick Conversion Tips and Tricks</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Use anchor points.</strong> Memorize a few exact conversions (1 inch = 2.54 cm, 1 kg = 2.2 lb, 1 mile = 1.6 km) and estimate from there.</li>
      <li><strong>Round for speed.</strong> In daily life, you rarely need four decimal places. Saying "1 kg is about 2.2 pounds" is precise enough for grocery shopping.</li>
      <li><strong>Watch for US vs. Imperial.</strong> A US gallon (3.785 L) is smaller than an Imperial gallon (4.546 L). US and Imperial fluid ounces also differ slightly. If you are following a British recipe, this matters.</li>
      <li><strong>Check the direction.</strong> The most common conversion mistake is multiplying when you should divide, or vice versa. Ask yourself: "Should my answer be a bigger or smaller number?" Inches to centimeters should get bigger. Pounds to kilograms should get smaller. If your answer goes the wrong direction, flip the operation.</li>
    </ul>

